page.title: 10LANDSCAPE AND BUILDINGS
page.content: Here we find open heathland, woodland glades, a tranquil pool managed by the Forest Commission and used like a country park by the general public. Howen Bottom valley is 125ft below surrounding moorland, while Bramshaw Telegraph is the highest point in the forest- 418ft above sea level. Fritham is a sprawling remote village, some of it is on open commonland, some surrounded by the pastureland of the farms situated astride a meandering undulating country lane, which terminates in a very picturesque car park and picnic area, from here the visitor can follow many footpaths. Most buildings are old,the Royal Oak dates from 1723.
